\hypertarget{load-the-octo-seq-raw-data-2m}{%
\section{Load the Octo Seq raw data
\textasciitilde2m}\label{load-the-octo-seq-raw-data-2m}}

Keep track of which data set you are working with. The code is written
so that you can run through the pipeline without having to worry about
changing variables (i.e.~data sets are imported to the variable ``all''
so that all the following commands will process the data without you
needing to change the variable each time)

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{all <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{Read10X}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{data.dir =} \StringTok{"D:/data/octo seq/Cellranger/OctoSeq2.1/raw_feature_bc_matrix"}\NormalTok{)}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{replace-gene-names-in-raw-data-with-ids-from-ccsv-file}{%
\section{replace gene names in raw data with IDs from ccsv
file}\label{replace-gene-names-in-raw-data-with-ids-from-ccsv-file}}

\hypertarget{takes-a-few-minutes}{%
\section{takes a few minutes}\label{takes-a-few-minutes}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{ref <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{read.csv}\NormalTok{(}\StringTok{"D:/data/octo seq/refMaster_040420.csv"}\NormalTok{,}\DataTypeTok{stringsAsFactors=}\OtherTok{FALSE}\NormalTok{)}

\NormalTok{ngenes <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(all}\OperatorTok{@}\NormalTok{Dimnames[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]])}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{ (g }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\NormalTok{ngenes)\{}
\NormalTok{  gene<-all}\OperatorTok{@}\NormalTok{Dimnames[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]][g]}
\NormalTok{  gene<-}\KeywordTok{substr}\NormalTok{(gene,}\DecValTok{6}\NormalTok{,}\KeywordTok{str_length}\NormalTok{(gene)}\OperatorTok{-}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{  ind<-}\KeywordTok{grep}\NormalTok{(gene,ref[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]])}
  \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ (}\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(ind)}\OperatorTok{>}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{) \{}
\NormalTok{    id <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{ref[[ind[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{],}\DecValTok{2}\NormalTok{]]}
    \ControlFlowTok{if}\NormalTok{ (}\KeywordTok{str_length}\NormalTok{(id)}\OperatorTok{>}\DecValTok{0}\NormalTok{) \{}
\NormalTok{      id <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{str_remove_all}\NormalTok{(id,}\StringTok{"}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}\textbackslash{}}\StringTok{("}\NormalTok{) }\CommentTok{# parentheses mess up gene names as dimensions}
\NormalTok{      id <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{str_remove_all}\NormalTok{(id,}\StringTok{"}\CharTok{\textbackslash{}\textbackslash{}}\StringTok{)"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{      id <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{substr}\NormalTok{(id,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{,}\DecValTok{60}\NormalTok{) }\CommentTok{# keep it short}
\NormalTok{      all}\OperatorTok{@}\NormalTok{Dimnames[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]][g]<-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{paste}\NormalTok{(id,gene,}\DataTypeTok{sep=}\StringTok{'-'}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{    \}}
\NormalTok{  \}}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{begin-quality-control-steps}{%
\section{Begin Quality Control
Steps}\label{begin-quality-control-steps}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{mito.genes <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{grep}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{pattern =} \StringTok{"^mt-"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{x =} \KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{x =}\NormalTok{ all), }\DataTypeTok{value =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{percent.mito <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Matrix}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{colSums}\NormalTok{(all) }\OperatorTok{/}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{Matrix}\OperatorTok{::}\KeywordTok{colSums}\NormalTok{(all)}
\NormalTok{all[[}\StringTok{"percent.mt"}\NormalTok{]] <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{PercentageFeatureSet}\NormalTok{(all, }\DataTypeTok{pattern =} \StringTok{"^MT-"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{all <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{subset}\NormalTok{(all, }\DataTypeTok{subset =}\NormalTok{ nFeature_RNA }\OperatorTok{>}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{200} \OperatorTok{&}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{nFeature_RNA }\OperatorTok{<}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{2500} \OperatorTok{&}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{percent.mt }\OperatorTok{<}\StringTok{ }\DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{plot1 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{FeatureScatter}\NormalTok{(all, }\DataTypeTok{feature1 =} \StringTok{"nCount_RNA"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{feature2 =} \StringTok{"percent.mt"}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{plot2 <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{FeatureScatter}\NormalTok{(all, }\DataTypeTok{feature1 =} \StringTok{"nCount_RNA"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{feature2 =} \StringTok{"nFeature_RNA"}\NormalTok{)}
\KeywordTok{CombinePlots}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{plots =} \KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{(plot1, plot2))}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{perform-linear-dimensional-reduction-pca-15-20m}{%
\section{Perform linear dimensional reduction (PCA)
\textasciitilde15-20m}\label{perform-linear-dimensional-reduction-pca-15-20m}}

I normally will create a new variable/Seurat object at this point and
rename it as ``all.norm'' so that I know that I have all of the
preprocesed data prior to running PCA, and I can manipulate the PCs etc
moving forward but still be able to go back to the processed data easily

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{all.norm <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{RunPCA}\NormalTok{(all, }\DataTypeTok{features =} \KeywordTok{VariableFeatures}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{object =}\NormalTok{ all), }\DataTypeTok{npcs =} \DecValTok{200}\NormalTok{)}

\hypertarget{this-sampling-strategy-randomly-permutes-a-subset-of-the-data-1-is-the-default-ad-erun-pca-constructing-a-null-distribution-of-feature-scores-and-repeat-this-procedure.-this-allows-an-identification-of-significant-pcs-as-those-who-have-a-strong-enrichment-of-low-p-value-features.}{%
\subsection{This sampling strategy randomly permutes a subset of the
data (1\% is the default) ad erun PCA, constructing a ``null
distribution'' of feature scores, and repeat this procedure. This allows
an identification of ``significant'' PCs as those who have a strong
enrichment of low p-value
features.}\label{this-sampling-strategy-randomly-permutes-a-subset-of-the-data-1-is-the-default-ad-erun-pca-constructing-a-null-distribution-of-feature-scores-and-repeat-this-procedure.-this-allows-an-identification-of-significant-pcs-as-those-who-have-a-strong-enrichment-of-low-p-value-features.}}

solid curve above the dashed line).

\hypertarget{cluster-the-cells}{%
\section{Cluster the cells}\label{cluster-the-cells}}

\hypertarget{seurat-v3-applies-a-graph-based-clustering-approach.-briefly-these-methods-embed-cells-in-a-graph-structure---for-example-a-k-nearest-neighbor-knn-graph-with-edges-drawn-between-cells-with-similar-feature-expression-patterns-and-then-attempt-to-partition-this-graph-into-highly-interconnected-quasi-cliques-or-communities}{%
\subsection{Seurat v3 applies a graph-based clustering approach.
Briefly, these methods embed cells in a graph structure - for example a
K-nearest neighbor (KNN) graph, with edges drawn between cells with
similar feature expression patterns, and then attempt to partition this
graph into highly interconnected ``quasi-cliques'' or
``communities''}\label{seurat-v3-applies-a-graph-based-clustering-approach.-briefly-these-methods-embed-cells-in-a-graph-structure---for-example-a-k-nearest-neighbor-knn-graph-with-edges-drawn-between-cells-with-similar-feature-expression-patterns-and-then-attempt-to-partition-this-graph-into-highly-interconnected-quasi-cliques-or-communities}}

\hypertarget{like-phenograph-a-knn-graph-is-constructed-based-on-the-elucidean-distance-in-pca-space.-then-the-findneighbors-function-refines-edge-weights-between-any-two-cells-based-on-the-shared-overlap-in-their-local-neighborhoods-this-is-referred-to-as-jaccard-similarity.-this-function-takes-the-previously-defined-input-regarding-number-of-pcs-now-dims}{%
\subsubsection{(like PhenoGraph), a KNN graph is constructed based on
the elucidean distance in PCA space. Then, the FindNeighbors function
refines edge weights between any two cells based on the shared overlap
in their local neighborhoods (this is referred to as Jaccard
similarity). This function takes the previously defined input regarding
number of PCs (now,
dims)}\label{like-phenograph-a-knn-graph-is-constructed-based-on-the-elucidean-distance-in-pca-space.-then-the-findneighbors-function-refines-edge-weights-between-any-two-cells-based-on-the-shared-overlap-in-their-local-neighborhoods-this-is-referred-to-as-jaccard-similarity.-this-function-takes-the-previously-defined-input-regarding-number-of-pcs-now-dims}}

\hypertarget{to-cluster-cells-seurat-applies-a-modularity-optimization-technique-such-as-louvain-algorithm-which-is-the-default-or-slm-to-iteratively-group-cells-together-with-the-goal-of-optimizing-the-standard-modularity-function.}{%
\subsection{To cluster cells, Seurat applies a modularity optimization
technique, such as Louvain algorithm (which is the default) or SLM, to
iteratively group cells together, with the goal of optimizing the
standard modularity
function.}\label{to-cluster-cells-seurat-applies-a-modularity-optimization-technique-such-as-louvain-algorithm-which-is-the-default-or-slm-to-iteratively-group-cells-together-with-the-goal-of-optimizing-the-standard-modularity-function.}}

\hypertarget{findclusters-implements-the-procedure-mentioned-above-and-contains-a-resolution-parameter-that-sets-granularity-of-downstream-clustering-with-increased-values-leading-to-a-greater-number-of-clusters.-typically-setting-the-parameter-between-0.4-1.2-typically-returns-good-results-for-single-cell-datasets-of-around-3k-cells.-clusters-could-be-found-using-the-idents-function.}{%
\subsubsection{FindClusters implements the procedure mentioned above and
contains a resolution parameter that sets ``granularity'' of downstream
clustering, with increased values leading to a greater number of
clusters. Typically, setting the parameter between 0.4-1.2 typically
returns good results for single-cell datasets of around 3K cells.
Clusters could be found using the Idents
function.}\label{findclusters-implements-the-procedure-mentioned-above-and-contains-a-resolution-parameter-that-sets-granularity-of-downstream-clustering-with-increased-values-leading-to-a-greater-number-of-clusters.-typically-setting-the-parameter-between-0.4-1.2-typically-returns-good-results-for-single-cell-datasets-of-around-3k-cells.-clusters-could-be-found-using-the-idents-function.}}

\subsection{Non-linear dimensional reduction techniques, such as tSNE
and UMAP, allows one to visualize and explore the datasets. The goal of
these algorithms is to learn the underlying manifold of the data in
order to place similar cells together in a low-dimensional space. Cells
within the graph-based clusters determined above should co-localize on
these dimension reduction plots. Seurat suggests using the same PCs as
what was provided as input to the clustering
analysis.}\label{non-linear-dimensional-reduction-techniques-such-as-tsne-and-umap-allows-one-to-visualize-and-explore-the-datasets.-the-goal-of-these-algorithms-is-to-learn-the-underlying-manifold-of-the-data-in-order-to-place-similar-cells-together-in-a-low-dimensional-space.-cells-within-the-graph-based-clusters-determined-above-should-co-localize-on-these-dimension-reduction-plots.-seurat-suggests-using-the-same-pcs-as-what-was-provided-as-input-to-the-clustering-analysis.}}

\#FindMarkers will find markers between two different identity groups -
you have to specify both identity groups. This is useful for comparing
the differences between two specific groups.

\#FindAllMarkers will find markers differentially expressed in each
identity group by comparing it to all of the others - you don't have to
manually define anything. Note that markers may bleed over between
closely-related groups - they are not forced to be specific to only one
group. This is what most people use (and likely what you want).

\hypertarget{grab-possible-nodes-using-findmarkers-from-seurat-object-assuming-youve-already-run-buildclustertree}{%
\section{Grab possible nodes using FindMarkers from seurat object,
assuming you've already run
BuildClusterTree()}\label{grab-possible-nodes-using-findmarkers-from-seurat-object-assuming-youve-already-run-buildclustertree}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{nodes <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{unique}\NormalTok{(all.normTREE}\OperatorTok{@}\NormalTok{tools}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{BuildClusterTree}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{edge[,}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{])}

\NormalTok{tree_markers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{()}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(nodes)) \{}
\CommentTok{#for(i in 1:2) \{}
\NormalTok{   tree_markers[[i]] <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{FindMarkers}\NormalTok{(}
\NormalTok{     all.normTREE, }\DataTypeTok{ident.1 =} \StringTok{"clustertree"}\NormalTok{, }\DataTypeTok{ident.2 =}\NormalTok{ nodes[i], }\DataTypeTok{min.pct=}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{selecting-markers-that-are-greater-than-log2-sorting-them-and-taking-10-most-neg-left-and-10-most-pos-right}{%
\section{selecting markers that are greater than log2, sorting them and
taking 10 most neg (left?) and 10 most pos
(right?)}\label{selecting-markers-that-are-greater-than-log2-sorting-them-and-taking-10-most-neg-left-and-10-most-pos-right}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{goodmarkers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{()}
\NormalTok{leftMarkers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{()}
\NormalTok{rightMarkers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{list}\NormalTok{()}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(nodes))\{}
\NormalTok{  these <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{tree_markers[[i]]}
\NormalTok{  these <-these[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{abs}\NormalTok{(these}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{avg_logFC)}\OperatorTok{>}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{),]}
\NormalTok{  these <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{these[}\KeywordTok{order}\NormalTok{(these}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{avg_logFC, }\DataTypeTok{decreasing =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{),]}
\NormalTok{  these}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{node_id <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{nodes[[i]]}
\NormalTok{  these}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{gene_id<-}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(these)}
\NormalTok{  leftMarkers[[i]] <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{head}\NormalTok{(these,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{  rightMarkers[[i]] <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{tail}\NormalTok{(these,}\DecValTok{3}\NormalTok{)}
\NormalTok{  goodmarkers[[i]] <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{these}

\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\hypertarget{concatenate-left-and-right-markers-for-all-nodes}{%
\section{concatenate left and right markers for all
nodes}\label{concatenate-left-and-right-markers-for-all-nodes}}

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\NormalTok{allmarkers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(goodmarkers[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]])}
\NormalTok{leftRightMarkers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(leftMarkers[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]]),}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(rightMarkers[[}\DecValTok{1}\NormalTok{]]))}
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{2}\OperatorTok{:}\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(nodes))\{}
\NormalTok{  allmarkers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(allmarkers,}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(goodmarkers[[i]]))}
\NormalTok{  leftRightMarkers <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{c}\NormalTok{(leftRightMarkers,}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(leftMarkers[[i]]),}\KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(rightMarkers[[i]]))}
  
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}

\#heatmap for each node individually

\begin{Shaded}
\begin{Highlighting}[]
\ControlFlowTok{for}\NormalTok{(i }\ControlFlowTok{in} \DecValTok{1}\OperatorTok{:}\KeywordTok{length}\NormalTok{(tree_markers))\{}
\NormalTok{  i}
\NormalTok{  these <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{tree_markers[[i]]}
\NormalTok{  these <-these[}\KeywordTok{which}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{abs}\NormalTok{(these}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{avg_logFC)}\OperatorTok{>}\FloatTok{0.5}\NormalTok{),]}
\NormalTok{  these <-}\StringTok{ }\NormalTok{these[}\KeywordTok{order}\NormalTok{(these}\OperatorTok{$}\NormalTok{avg_logFC, }\DataTypeTok{decreasing =} \OtherTok{TRUE}\NormalTok{),]}
\NormalTok{  these <-}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{rbind}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{head}\NormalTok{(these,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{),}\KeywordTok{tail}\NormalTok{(these,}\DecValTok{10}\NormalTok{))}
\KeywordTok{print}\NormalTok{(these)}
   \KeywordTok{print}\NormalTok{(}\KeywordTok{DoHeatmap}\NormalTok{(all.normTREE, }\DataTypeTok{features =} \KeywordTok{rownames}\NormalTok{(these))}\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{NoLegend}\NormalTok{() }\OperatorTok{+}\StringTok{ }\KeywordTok{theme}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{axis.text.y =} \KeywordTok{element_text}\NormalTok{(}\DataTypeTok{size =} \DecValTok{5}\NormalTok{)))}
  
\NormalTok{\}}
\end{Highlighting}
\end{Shaded}
